Hi, Michele.

As Michele wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/23/2004 at 00:50:20 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>If I am asked the probability of sell at least two dishwashers in 
>any given week given the table  No of d/w sold     No of weeks
>                                      0                20
>                                      1                15
>                                      2                10
>                                      3                 4
>                                      4                 1
>does at least mean 2,3,or 4 being 1x15/50 .3
>or does it mean 0,1,2 up to but no more than being 1x10/50 .2
>
>[Difficulty]
>If somebody says at get me at least 3 marbles they do not want 1 or 
>2 but three, does this mean 4 will even do or does at least 3 mean 
>up to and including 3
>
>[Thoughts]
>Not sure if I was asked to get somebody at least 3 I would think 
>they wanted 3 or more but not sure if in statistics this means at 
>least 3 but no more.

"At least 3" means "no less than 3," which is the same as "3 or 
more," as you guessed. If they wanted at least 3 but no more, that 
would be "exactly 3".

In your first example, if they meant 0,1,2 up to but no more than 2, 
that would be "at most 2" or "no more than 2."

